.‚†Ä
Looking for something fun and healthy to do over the holidays? I got you covered! Not only is this idea super cute but it‚Äôs very practical.‚†Ä

I shared this fruit tree with my friends the other day and it was a total hit! üòã It‚Äôs very easy to grab the fruit off the toothpicks and of course aesthetically pleasing.‚†Ä

What you need:‚†Ä
1 pineapple‚†Ä

Step 3 - Prepare the colorful fruit. Cut the tops off of strawberries and cut kiwis into slices.‚†Ä
Step 4 - Use toothpicks to stick the fruit around the pineapple and pear. Use a toothpick to stick the pineapple star on the very top.‚†Ä

Whenever I do a Q&A, I get asked how some people can eat whatever they want and never gain weight. So, let‚Äôs explore that.

The answer is quite simple: they are not in a caloric surplus. But there are different ways that might be the case, so let‚Äôs dig in a little further.

The first way is that they‚Äôre just not eating a ton. Sure, they might get McDonald‚Äôs 5 days per week and snack on Oreos throughout the day, but their overall calories might actually be pretty low. While their diet might not be the ‚Äúhealthiest‚Äù, they‚Äôre not over-consuming. Even though it looks like they‚Äôre eating a ton, they‚Äôre actually not from a caloric standpoint.

The second way is that their diet is actually well-rounded, but you‚Äôre just seeing the ‚Äújunk‚Äù. If your coworker is always snacking on cookies and donuts in the office, you might think their diet is garbage. But when they go home, they might actually eat very well. Take it from someone who follows flexible dieting- just because you see someone eating less than optimal food, it doesn‚Äôt mean their whole diet looks like that.

The other ways this might be the case revolve around energy expenditure. Someone might simply have a higher BMR, meaning they require more calories throughout the day. Yes, genetics do play a role to some extent, and someone might naturally have a higher metabolism. But things like age, muscle mass, and even hormones, all play a role in our individual calorie requirements.

Lastly, someone might simply be a very active person. That kid you grew up with that could eat everything in sight was likely also extremely active. I‚Äôve talked about NEAT before: a nurse might eat a lot more than a telemarketer, since they are on the feet all day and therefore burning more calories throughout the day.

‚òïÔ∏èCoffee doesn't just keep you awake - it may also make you smarter. Many studies have examined the effects of caffeine on the brain, demonstrating that caffeine can temporarily improve mood, reaction time, memory, vigilance and general brain function.
..
‚òïÔ∏èCaffeine blocks an inhibitory neurotransmitter in the brain, which has a stimulating effect. Controlled studies show that caffeine improves both mood and brain function.
..
‚òïÔ∏èCaffeine raises metabolic rate and helps mobilise fatty acids from fat tissues. It can also enhance physical performance.
..
‚òïÔ∏èDrinking coffee is associated with a drastically reduced risk of type 2 diabetes. People who drink several cups per day are the least likely to develop diabetes. In prospective studies, coffee drinkers have up to a 60% lower risk of Alzheimer's and dementia.
..
‚òïÔ∏èCoffee appears to be protective against certain liver disorders, lowering the risk of liver cancer by 40% and cirrhosis by as much as 80%. One recent study showed that coffee drinkers had a 30% lower risk of death during a 20-year period.
..
‚òïÔ∏èCoffee contains antioxidants, vitamins B and minerals‚Ä¶ For most people, coffee can be a healthy part of the diet. It is fine to enjoy a couple of cups a day.
..
However, coffee  may not be beneficial for everyone. Those with certain heart conditions, caffeine sensitivity, and women who are pregnant should stick to decaf or tea.

There is no deeper meaning to this comparison‚Ä¶ this is simply to compare the nutritional profiles of these 2 burger options.

I fully understand that you may prefer a plant-based option. Or you may only want to eat meat. Or you may hate fast food and think it‚Äôs all terrible for you. That‚Äôs all fine- I‚Äôm not here to tell you how to eat. And unless you‚Äôve hired someone to tell you how to eat, those decisions should always be up to you.

But I do know that a lot of people out there assume that the plant-based option is automatically healthier from a nutritional standpoint, so I want to share this comparison to show you that may or may not be true.

Nutritionally, these options are incredibly similar, and neither stands out as a clear-cut ‚Äúbetter‚Äù option. Since the sandwiches are built exactly the same in terms of bun and condiments, you can see that the Impossible Burger patty has 30 less calories, 6g less fat, 3g less protein, and 9g more carbs.

The one thing I will add that isn‚Äôt evident in this comparison is that plant-based meat is very heavily processed. If processed food is something you deem unhealthy (which according to recent comments, a lot of people do) then you may want to think twice before picking up an Impossible Burger.

All that being said, have you had an Impossible Burger? Either at Burger King or elsewhere? I‚Äôve tried it once and did not really enjoy it, but am willing to give it another shot

Which one surprised you?üòÖ üî∫Many people want to lose weight, but many are confused & don‚Äôt know what to believe. That‚Äôs why I created this quick reference for you.
.
.
üíØ The truth is, in order for you to lose weight, you need to be in a daily caloric deficit. These are many ways achieve that. Through portion control, daily movement & resistance training is ideal. Ultimately for you to keep the weight off, it will be about creating lifestyle habits that you can continue long term.
.
.
üí¶ RUNNING - Yes it‚Äôs okay for burning calories...but it‚Äôs not the most effective method. Interval training crushes it for many reasons (see my recent post for a deeper explanation) mainly more lean muscle tissue while burning fat & more calories is a shorter time.
.
.
üçπJUICE/CLEANSES - The only reason people lose weight with these, is because they‚Äôre consuming significantly less calories than they did prior.
.
.
üïòEATING TIME - If you‚Äôre not hungry at night, then don‚Äôt eat. But don‚Äôt do it because you‚Äôve been told it makes you fat. As long as you‚Äôre in a daily caloric deficit, you can consume meals at any time. A 400 calorie meal is the same 400 calories at 10am as it is at 10pm.
.
.
üçΩSKIPPING MEALS - If you like to eat every 2 hours you can do that. If you only like to eat once per day (like I do aka ‚Äúintermittent fasting‚Äù) that‚Äôs totally fine too. It simply doesn‚Äôt matter...as long as you‚Äôre still taking in the same calories, go with a frequency you prefer.
.
.
üçûCARBS - While carbohydrates have been demonized, they can certainly be consumed on any weight loss plan. How refined they are makes a difference in how you‚Äôll feel, perform, digest, however simply eating carbohydrates won‚Äôt make you gain weight. Opt for less refined carbs (fruit, veggies) when possible.
.
.
üî•SWEAT BELTS - These do nothing, besides make you sweat in that area. You're're not burning fat, nor losing weight because of it. ___________________
